## 🔐 Reflecting on Breach Events to Justify Privacy Controls

## 🎯 Why It Matters

Referencing recent data breaches strengthens your business case for privacy controls by:
- Demonstrating **real-world risk relevance**
- Supporting **justification of control implementation**
- Showing awareness of emerging threats during **risk assessments**, **ATO packages**, or **continuous monitoring**

---

## 🔍 Real Breach Events to Reference (2023–2025)

| Breach/Event                          | Summary                                                         | Privacy Lessons                                                                 |
|---------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **MOVEit Transfer (2023)**            | Exploited zero-day vulnerability in file transfer software      | Justifies secure file handling (AC-17), patching (SI-2), and encryption (SC-12) |
| **T-Mobile (2023 breach + prior)**    | Repeated PII breaches due to weak encryption and access control | Reinforces need for SC-12, AC-6, AU-2                                           |
| **Meta (Facebook)**                   | Hefty fines for mismanagement of user consent and tracking      | Supports governance and privacy notices (PL-8, AR family controls)              |
| **SolarWinds (supply chain breach)**  | Attack on software update process                               | Encourages supply chain vetting and privacy impact assessments                  |

---

## 📈 Sample GRC Justification (SAR or SSP Insert)

> _“Given high-profile incidents like MOVEit and T-Mobile, where inadequate encryption and weak access controls led to significant personal data loss, 
the implementation of privacy-enhancing controls such as SC-12, SC-28, and AC-6 is essential for risk reduction and mission assurance.”_

